["A. Validate the alert.
1. Inspect the users that were compromised and any unfamiliar processes or applications that might have caused credential access.
2. Inspect the lateral movement path to ensure domain takeover does not occur.
3. Check for other suspicious activities in the timeline.

B. Scope the incident. Find related accounts and devices in the incident graph.

C. Contain and mitigate the breach. Decommission compromised accounts or reset passwords. Quarantine affected devices to prevent lateral movement.

D. Contact your incident response team or contact Microsoft support for investigation and remediation services."]

{"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.Category":"Ransomware","MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationId":null,"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationState":"UnsupportedAlertType","LastUpdated":"06/20/2024 09:38:35","IncidentId":"107","DetectionSource":"WindowsDefenderAtp","AssignedTo":"Defender Experts","Determination":null,"Classification":null,"Action":"There is no one-size-fits-all response if you have been victimized by ransomware. There is no guarantee that handing over the ransom will give you access to your files again. Paying the ransom could also make you a target for more malware.

•	Contact your incident response team.
NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team, contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic investigation. A forensic investigation is important to identify Indicators of Compromise (IoC) that may be used to prevent other machines from installing the malware.
•	Check if files on the affected machine were encrypted by ransomware.
        o	If files were encrypted, disconnect the machine from the network as soon as possible.
•	Check for other suspicious events in the machine timeline.
•	Check for the observed deleted file name or SHA1 on other machines in the network.
•	Find the infection source and block it (IP or email)
•	Rebuild the affected machine.
•	After the affected machine has been rebuilt: 
         o	Ensure your software has the latest patch, update your malware signatures, and close the vectors of attack.
         o	Move out-of-date applications to other systems to reduce the attack surface.
         o	Configure your Trust Center to disable macros.","ThreatName":null,"ThreatFamilyName":null,"DetectorId":"ca3d4939-c0fe-4a2f-8ebd-48a0ac00e0aa","MitreTechniques":"T1490","ProcessedBySentinel":"True","Alert generation status":"Full alert created"}

{"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.Category":"Ransomware","MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationId":null,"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationState":"UnsupportedAlertType","LastUpdated":"06/20/2024 09:38:35","IncidentId":"107","DetectionSource":"WindowsDefenderAtp","AssignedTo":"Defender Experts","Determination":null,"Classification":null,"Action":"There is no one-size-fits-all response if you have been victimized by ransomware. There is no guarantee that handing over the ransom will give you access to your files again. Paying the ransom could also make you a target for more malware.

•	Contact your incident response team.
NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team, contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic investigation. A forensic investigation is important to identify Indicators of Compromise (IoC) that may be used to prevent other machines from installing the malware.
•	Check if files on the affected machine were encrypted by ransomware.
        o	If files were encrypted, disconnect the machine from the network as soon as possible.
•	Check for other suspicious events in the machine timeline.
•	Check for the observed deleted file name or SHA1 on other machines in the network.
•	Find the infection source and block it (IP or email)
•	Rebuild the affected machine.
•	After the affected machine has been rebuilt:
